{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505733"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:34:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2472"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2472"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.39,0.22,0.14,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2472"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64449"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"},{"type":"tags","id":"9040"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27100"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EYou are working with the MedStar retrieval team and have been called to a motor vehicle accident in rural Australia. The patient is a 36-year-old man who was the driver that hit another vehicle, both travelling 90 kmph. He has been trapped in the driver\u0027s seat for several hours with his legs pinned. As you arrived the fire service is freeing him from the vehicle. You note his respiratory rate is 6/min, O2 saturations 90%, pulse 150/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg and temperature 38.0C. His airway is not protected and you prepare for Rapid Sequence Induction at the road side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following induction regimens is most suitable?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Propofol, fentanyl and suxamethonium","Ketamine hydrochloride and rocuronium","Ketamine hydrochloride and suxamethonium","Propofol, fentanyl, and rocuronium","Ketamine hydrochloride, midazolam and suxamethonium"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question aims to test the candidates knowledge of common anaesthetic agents and their relative contraindications. In the case, it is critical to appreciate the patient has a crush injury and very likely rhabdomyolysis upon being freed from the vehicle. Part of the disease process means the serum potassium will be high. In the list of medications, suxamethonium is the most likely to worsen this as it is a depolarising muscle relaxant; meaning it will also increase the potassium level as well myalgia and possible muscle breakdown in the legs. This patient is critically unwell and inducing a life threatening electrolyte abnormality in a retrieval setting will greatly reduce their chance of survival. Despite suxamethonium\u2019s rapid onset-offset, which would be useful in the patient, it would be much safer to use a non-depolarising muscle relaxant such as rocuronium. The other consideration is that this patient is probably haemodynamically unstable. Most anaesthetic agents cause hypotension however \u003Cstrong\u003Eketamine\u003C/strong\u003E does not and would be an ideal agent in this case. Thus the best combination is ketamine and rocuronium, as the former will avoid further haemodynamic instability and the latter will not raise potassium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note there is a minimal risk of rhabdomyolysis with ketamine and propofol also through unknown mechanisms but this risk is much less than that of suxamethonium. Midazolam can be used in anaesthetic procedures but this is commonly in minor \u0027sedation\u0027 procedures and it is used because of its anxiolytic and sedative effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Depolarising muscle relaxants can cause myalgia and hyperkalaemia.","Ketamine is a suitable induction agent in haemodynamically unstable patients due to its sympathomimetic properties."],"references":["Torres PA, Helmstetter JA, Kaye AM, Kaye AD. Rhabdomyolysis: pathogenesis, diagnosis, and treatment. Ochsner J. 2015 Spring;15(1):58-69. PMID: 25829882; PMCID: PMC4365849. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25829882/","Gupta A, Thorson P, Penmatsa KR, Gupta P. Rhabdomyolysis: Revisited. Ulster Med J. 2021 May;90(2):61-69. Epub 2021 Jul 8. PMID: 34276082; PMCID: PMC8278949. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8278949/","Stanley M, Chippa V, Aeddula NR, Quintanilla Rodriguez BS, Adigun R. Rhabdomyolysis. 2024 Dec 11. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846335. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28846335/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64449"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64449"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T14:52:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T14:52:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2472"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79097"}}},"meta":{"canDel